==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Theory
<hw>The"o*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Theories</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F.
<ets>th⟦eacute⟧orie</ets>, L. <ets>theoria</ets>, Gr. <?/ a beholding,
spectacle, contemplation, speculation, fr. <?/ a spectator, <?/ to see,
view. See <er>Theater</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A doctrine, or
scheme of things, which terminates in speculation or contemplation,
without a view to practice; hypothesis; speculation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧This word is employed by English writers in a
very loose and improper sense. It is with them usually convertible into
<xex>hypothesis</xex>, and <xex>hypothesis</xex> is commonly used as
another term for <xex>conjecture</xex>. The terms <xex>theory</xex> and
<xex>theoretical</xex> are properly used in opposition to the terms
<xex>practice</xex> and <xex>practical</xex>. In this sense, they were
exclusively employed by the ancients; and in this sense, they are almost
exclusively employed by the Continental philosophers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir
W. Hamilton.</au></rj> </note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An exposition of the general or abstract principles
of any science; <as>as, the <ex>theory</ex> of music</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The science, as distinguished from the art; <as>as,
the <ex>theory</ex> and practice of medicine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The philosophical explanation of phenomena, either
physical or moral; <as>as, Lavoisier's <ex>theory</ex> of combustion;
Adam Smith's <ex>theory</ex> of moral sentiments.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Atomic theory</b></col>, <col><b>Binary
theory</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Atomic</er>,
<er>Binary</er>, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hypothesis, speculation.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Theory</er>, <er>Hypothesis</er>. A <xex>theory</xex> is a scheme of
the relations subsisting between the parts of a systematic whole; an
<xex>hypothesis</xex> is a tentative conjecture respecting a cause of
phenomena.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Theosopher</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Theosoph</ent>⟦br⟧
